                            <h1>Michael Zhao St. Therese My Chinatown, my story... Grade 8</h1>

                            <p>I was amazed by the buildings’ styles the first time I visited Chinatown. Many of the buildings are made of tan or rufous bricks. On top of these buildings, there are spires which look like the tops of pavilions. Since many buildings are architecturally similar to each other, they create a visual beauty to me. </p>

<p>During the weekends, I usually visit Chinatown with my friends for fun. From my perspective, the heart of Chinatown is around Cermak Road, Wentworth Avenue, and Archer Avenue. In that area, you can not only find cafe, teahouses, and dim sum spots but also you can find stores for shopping Chinese stuff such as teapot, mooncake, and Chinese lantern. </p>

<p>Restaurants in Chinatown are really good. Every restaurant in Chinatown has its unique characteristics. Sze Chuan Cuisine, for example, has spicy dishes which come from Sichuan, southwest of China. Sichuan also is well-known for its usage of hot pepper, so all the dishes always have a common ingredient, hot pepper. Since I like to eat spicy food, I love many of the restaurants in Chinatown. The ice cream in Legend Tasty House also tastes amazing. Finally, Strings Ramen Shop is also one of my favorite restaurants in Chinatown. This restaurant is decorated by lanterns. The wall, tables, benches are all made of wood. Whenever I go to Strings Ramen Shop, I instantly feel cozy. All this restaurant’s noodle dishes are delicious. I love Miso ramen noodle the most because of its nice salty soup and flavored meat.</p>

<p>In conclusion, although I have only lived in Chicago Chinatown for one and a half years, I consider Chinatown to be a vital / crucial part of my life. I have made so many memories and gone to a lot of unforgettable events at this place. It has become such an important part of my US experience.</p>
